Women who work in the home and are economically dependent on their husbands are given considerably less choice in deciding whether or not to be divorced. Young, working women have multiple intimate partners and choose not to get married because they see marriage as restraining. Sri Lankan feminists have claimed throughout the twentieth century that divorce during the eighteen hundreds were difficult to obtain because of the Chiththya Law. Women were “not vested with all the rights her husband did. Women as the dependents of her husband, lived under subjugation and dependent.”[59]

Three decades after the passing of divorce laws, the Act of 1971 gives more than adequate protection to the wife.[58] This act was passed in the wake of numerous studies that have found the high rate of marital separations which constitute a problem for the survival of the family system.[58] By granting more rights to women through this act there are less chances of the woman’s children falling into dysfunctional families.[58] Yet currently there are no statistics which state that families are separating at a high rate. It is difficult to determine the reasons for the decrease in divorce rates because of the lack of reliable statistics, but explanations that have often been put forth include a decrease in the age at marriage, parents’ involvement in Mongolian capital cities and the subjective emotional element of marriage.[58] The Cambodian government has made efforts to decrease divorce rates through the changing of their criminal code.
